ve from an obsession with style, packaging and synthetic sounds to content, socially conscious lyrics and a new authenticity. This edition is framed by a prologue by Tara Brabazon, asking how we can reclaim the spirit, energy and authenticity of Madchester for a post-youth, post-pop generation. It is illustrated with iconic photographs by Kevin Cummins.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPopular musicxSocial aspects. 0aPopular musicy1981-1990xHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musiczEnglandzManchesterxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  a1980s.  aAcid House.  aCultural Studies.  aHaçienda.  aJean Baudrillard.  aMadchester.  aManchester.  aPop music.  aPost-pop.  aYouth culture.1 aRedhead, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615436140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526154361423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526154361/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles